{"version":2,"kind":"Article","sha256":"d878c01b55a9efee7c33161cb7bc29ef5e9a42d4b117714473366fbc060123ba","slug":"index","location":"/index.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Critical Zone Science","content_includes_title":false,"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"index.md","url":"/index-a263151602f59fdaa519a689c5195693.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Class notes for the GEOL 313: Critical Zone Science class.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"w1KcwpEf7n"}],"key":"vIQGhn4HVk"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This course introduces and examines the Critical Zone (CZ), Earth’s permeable layer that extends from the top of vegetation to the bottom of the fresh groundwater zone. It is a constantly evolving boundary layer where rock, soil, water, air, and living organisms interact to regulate the landscape and natural habitats, and determine the availability of life-sustaining resources, including our food production and water quality. CZ science is a highly interdisciplinary and international pursuit that depends upon effective and informed trans-disciplinary science. This course format includes readings, discussions, presentations, and learning activities and utilizes  large quantity of interdisciplinary data available from the existing National Science Foundation (NSF)-funded CZ Observatories (CZO).","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"spXC2BKTev"}],"key":"rWehGoT0ka"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"At the end of the course students will be able to:","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"k